article.description:
Tim Thomas scored 21 points, including five in
overtime, and Ray Allen had 20 as the Milwaukee Bucks ended
Philadelphia's four-game winning streak with a 110-105 victory
Saturday night.
article.headline: Bucks overcome Iverson's 31 points in victory
article.linkText: Thomas, Bucks end 76ers' four-game win streak in OT
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Michael Redd enjoyed playing in what he considered "a wild game.''
Redd

Redd and three teammates came off the bench to combined for 45 points, leading the Milwaukee Bucks to a 110-105 overtime victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Saturday night. "A wild game, that's for sure, and it's fun when we win those,'' Redd said after scoring 16 points. "This swings the momentum. We broke the curse tonight.'' He referred to Philadelphia's four straight wins, and victories in 13 of the 17 previous meetings with the Bucks. Tim Thomas scored 21 points, including five in overtime, Ray Allen had 20 and Sam Cassell 16 to lead the starters. But it was the 16 points by both Redd and Toni Kukoc, plus a combined 13 from Jason Caffey and Kevin Ollie, that gave the Bucks a 45-20 advantage off the bench. "It's a deep team,'' Milwaukee coach George Karl said, "so every night is probably going to be different. I think I have 10 or 11 guys who are finishers, but you can't play 10 guys, so the matchups and the circumstances of the game and the production will determine who's going to play.'' Allen Iverson led the 76ers with 31 points on 11-of-27 shooting. Keith Van Horn had 22 points, Todd MacCulloch and Eric Snow 12 each, and Greg Buckner and Brian Skinner 10 apiece. Iverson, however, was held without a point in overtime. "He's so fast, it's unbelievable,'' said Ollie, who spent a lot of time chasing Iverson. "He's an amazing player and guarding him is quite a chore. "But we made him take some tough shots and I think we did a good job on him. He takes so many shots, you know he's going to make a lot.'' The Bucks, who led most of the game, fell behind 78-76 early in the fourth quarter before scoring nine straight points to start a 13-2 run for an 89-80 lead with 5:12 to play. It was 93-84 when the 76ers made another run, getting within one with eight straight points. But a free throw by Cassell and a field goal by Thomas on a slam of a missed 3-pointer by Redd made it 96-92 with 57 seconds left. Then Iverson took over, making two free throws, stealing a pass and going the length of the court for a tying layup with 33 seconds left. He also rebounded the final shot by Milwaukee before missing a game-winning shot at the buzzer in regulation. In the overtime, the Bucks built a six-point lead only to have the 76ers score five quick points to make it 104-103. Thomas scored on a slam for a three-point lead with 44 seconds left, and the Bucks wrapped it up with free throws -- one each by Thomas and Redd and two by Cassell. "Tim's tip was big-time,'' Karl said. The Bucks scored the final eight points of the first quarter to take a 27-19 lead. After the 76ers closed to 39-37, Thomas scored seven points in a 12-0 run and the Bucks led 55-45 at halftime. The 76ers never led by more than two points and trailed by as many as 14, yet still managed to force overtime while shooting 45 percent to Milwaukee's 54 percent from the field. "We had so many bad shots in the first half,'' Philadelphia coach Larry Brown said. "That was the result of us not sharing the ball. We got down and then had to spend so much energy t catch up. I love the fact they never give up, but I we should learn from tonight.'' Snow said, "We showed heart by coming back. We fought back, but they made a couple of big plays on both ends down the stretch.'' Van Horn said overtime isn't what the 76ers needed when looking at a schedule that has them playing 12 games in 16 days. "We missed opportunities and they made the plays in overtime,'' he said, "but we can't be playing too many overtimes. Game notes
Kukoc has hit 33.6 percent on 3-pointers in his career but is 13-for-22 in his first five games with the Bucks. ... Iverson reached double figures for the 127th straight game, the longest such streak among active players. ... Instant replay was used at the end of the second quarter, with the officials deciding that Milwaukee's basket was too late.
